{"id": "130301", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=130301", "title": "Farron Coal", "text": "The Farron Coal is a in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nAvailability.\nFound in the &lt;a href=\"Road%20of%20Sacrifices\"&gt;Road of Sacrifices&lt;/a&gt; on what once was the eastern access to the keep. The area can be reached by following the eastern shore of the marsh, fighting a couple of &lt;a href=\"Lycanthrope\"&gt;Lycanthrope&lt;/a&gt;s along the way. The coal can be found at the end of a blocked passageway, guarded by a &lt;a href=\"Black%20Knight%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Black Knight&lt;/a&gt;.\nUsage.\nThe coal can be given to &lt;a href=\"Blacksmith%20Andre\"&gt;Blacksmith Andre&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Firelink%20Shrine%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Firelink Shrine&lt;/a&gt; to allow usage of the following gems for infusions:"}
{"id": "133926", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=133926", "title": "Farron Dart", "text": "Farron Dart is a &lt;a href=\"Sorcery%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;sorcery&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nEffect.\nA miniaturized version of &lt;a href=\"Soul%20Arrow%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Soul Arrow&lt;/a&gt;. Fires a soul dart at the target, dealing 0.52 times the catalyst's &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Buff\"&gt;Spell Buff&lt;/a&gt; as &lt;a href=\"Magic%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Magic&lt;/a&gt; damage. The dart deals little damage and cannot inflict &lt;a href=\"stagger\"&gt;stagger&lt;/a&gt; on their targets, but cost very little &lt;a href=\"Focus%20Points\"&gt;FP&lt;/a&gt; and cast extremely quickly.\nUnlike other Soul Arrow variants, Farron Dart can be cast while &lt;a href=\"rolling\"&gt;rolling&lt;/a&gt; and running.\n&lt;br&gt;"}
{"id": "133925", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=133925", "title": "Farron Flashsword", "text": "Farron Flashsword is a &lt;a href=\"Sorcery%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;sorcery&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nAvailability.\nSold by &lt;a href=\"Orbeck%20of%20Vinheim\"&gt;Orbeck of Vinheim&lt;/a&gt; for 5,000 &lt;a href=\"Soul%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;souls&lt;/a&gt;.\nEffect.\nConjures a sword made of souls from the staff and swings it quickly, dealing 1.03 times the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Buff\"&gt;Spell Buff&lt;/a&gt; of the catalyst as &lt;a href=\"Magic%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Magic&lt;/a&gt; damage to any enemy struck by the blade.\nUse.\nFarron Flashsword, while not as strong or possessing as much range as &lt;a href=\"Soul%20Greatsword%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Soul Greatsword&lt;/a&gt;, has the potential to be a very potent spell, as the true power behind the spell lies within its utility.\nWhen cast, it mimics the attack pattern of a &lt;a href=\"Straight%20Swords%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;straight sword&lt;/a&gt;, and the caster can even perform running and rolling attacks. The sword can be swung in quick succession repeatedly, as the &lt;a href=\"Focus%20Points\"&gt;FP&lt;/a&gt; cost is very minimal, and the slashes are relatively-quick to cast and can chain together effectively.\nWith a high pool of &lt;a href=\"Intelligence%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt;, the damage of each slash can be on par with what a &lt;a href=\"Crystal%20Gem\"&gt;Crystal&lt;/a&gt;-infused straight sword is capable of. These traits allow sorcerers to have a reliable, and effective, close-quarters tool for dispatching of foes that close in on them, instead of having to run the risk of using ranged Sorceries at close range. Mixing Farron Flashsword with Soul Greatsword is an effective way to deal with aggressive enemies, and in terms of &lt;a href=\"Player%20versus%20Player%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;PvP&lt;/a&gt;, disorient or otherwise catch players off-guard.\nHowever, there is a catch to using this sorcery; since it behaves like a straight sword when in use, it is able to be &lt;a href=\"Parry%20and%20Riposte%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;parried&lt;/a&gt; much like one. This should be taken into consideration before engaging an enemy that can parry the caster or dons a &lt;a href=\"Parry%20%28skill%29\"&gt;parrying&lt;/a&gt; shield.\nNotes.\n&lt;br&gt;"}
{"id": "142979", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=142979", "title": "Farron Follower", "text": "Farron Followers (\u30d5\u30a1\u30e9\u30f3\u306e\u5e7d\u9b3c \"Farron no Y\u016bki\", Phantoms of Farron) are in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;a href=\"Ashes%20of%20Ariandel\"&gt;Ashes of Ariandel&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDescription.\nFarron Followers are members of the &lt;a href=\"Undead%20Legion%20of%20Farron\"&gt;Undead Legion of Farron&lt;/a&gt;, as the &lt;a href=\"Abyss%20Watchers\"&gt;Abyss Watchers&lt;/a&gt; are, but unlike them, they wield other weapons and attack with a different combat style, favoring to use throwing spears or short swords to fight. Just as the Abyss Watchers do, they will fight with each other whenever one of them is corrupted by the &lt;a href=\"Abyss\"&gt;Abyss&lt;/a&gt;.\nTypes.\nThere are four different types of Farron Followers:\nFollower Lancer.\nThe most common Follower. This enemy wields the &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Javelin\"&gt;Follower Javelin&lt;/a&gt; and will spend most of their time throwing javelins at the player from range. Their high aggro range means that unless the player is aware of their presence, the first warning that a Lancer nearby is a spear striking them.\nFollower Knight.\nThis Follower wields a &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Javelin\"&gt;Follower Javelin&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Shield\"&gt;Follower Shield&lt;/a&gt;. They will generally run into melee range to attack the player with their spear, using their shield to block incoming attacks.\nFollower Torchman.\nThis enemy wields a &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Torch\"&gt;Follower Torch&lt;/a&gt;, using the weapon art to breath fire at the player in arcs. He can also scream to alert other Followers once he is alerted to the player's presence.\nFollower Swordsman.\nThis Follower wields a &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Torch\"&gt;Follower Torch&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Sabre\"&gt;Follower Sabre&lt;/a&gt;. He will not use his torch's skill but will attack with fast and fluid combos using the sabre.\nLocations.\nFarron Followers can be found in multiple locations throughout the &lt;a href=\"Painted%20World%20of%20Ariandel\"&gt;Painted World of Ariandel&lt;/a&gt;. They are initially encountered in the Snowfield area shortly after arriving in Ariandel, and later in larger numbers in the Snowy Mountain Pass.\nLore.\nThe Farron Follower were a group affiliated with Farron's Undead Legion, whose core were the &lt;a href=\"Abyss%20Watchers\"&gt;Abyss Watchers&lt;/a&gt;, and performed an essential function for them. In fact, the warriors of Farron could have been corrupted by the &lt;a href=\"Abyss\"&gt;Abyss&lt;/a&gt; they fought and to which they were exposed and consequently the Followers had the task of hunting them down, even before they lost their human aspect and just showed traces of being infected. For this reason the group developed equipment and techniques suited to the role. The Followers would hunt the corrupted warriors in groups, surrounding them and then engaging their target while they shielded themselves with &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Shield\"&gt;shields&lt;/a&gt; imbued with resistance to the Dark.. They would then fight their enemies thrusting their &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Javelin\"&gt;spears&lt;/a&gt; to keep the distance or in close combat with &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Sabre\"&gt;sabres&lt;/a&gt;. On a final command, they would have hurled their spears at their fallen foe, to give the retired warrior an honorable send-off, implying that their role was nevertheless charged with importance to the continued functioning of the Undead Legion and respect for their members even when they fell to the Dark. The Followers also used &lt;a href=\"Follower%20Torch\"&gt;offensive torches&lt;/a&gt; to purge the Abyss that manifested inside the bodies in the form of &lt;a href=\"Pus%20of%20Man\"&gt;Pus&lt;/a&gt;, treating it with fire as was ancient tradition.\nHowever at some point the Abyss Watchers were called to become &lt;a href=\"Lords%20of%20Cinder\"&gt;Lords of Cinder&lt;/a&gt;, sacrificing their shared power in the &lt;a href=\"Soul%20of%20the%20Blood%20of%20the%20Wolf\"&gt;wolf blood&lt;/a&gt; to link the fading &lt;a href=\"First%20Flame\"&gt;First Flame&lt;/a&gt; and then be buried with a fragment of its &lt;a href=\"Cinders%20of%20a%20Lord\"&gt;cinders&lt;/a&gt; still burning. Over time, the land of &lt;a href=\"Farron%20Keep\"&gt;Farron&lt;/a&gt;, where the bodies of countless warriors of the past were buried, fell into ruin and became a rotten and poisonous forest, and the remaining acolytes of the Undead Legion were corrupted along with it becoming &lt;a href=\"Ghru\"&gt;Ghru&lt;/a&gt;s. The Farron Followers consequently had lost their role and reason to exist along with their home and became forlorns, unwanted souls that died and survived as a wandering pack of &lt;a href=\"Hollow\"&gt;Hollow&lt;/a&gt;s. They kept drifting aimlessly until they were eventually drawn into the &lt;a href=\"Painted%20World%20of%20Ariandel\"&gt;Painted World of Ariandel&lt;/a&gt;, where they were welcomed by the other lost souls and found refuge.\nAs the &lt;a href=\"First%20Flame\"&gt;First Flame&lt;/a&gt; continued to fade and &lt;a href=\"Lothric%2C%20Younger%20Prince\"&gt;Prince Lothric&lt;/a&gt; refused to link it, the Lords of Cinder of the past were exhumed from their graves to once again be used as fuel. Among them the Abyss Watchers rose from their graves too but refused to sacrifice themselves to link the Fire again, choosing to return to their Keep in Farron. However, the Followers were no longer present to cull the warriors that would become corrupted by the Abyss, consequently forcing the Watchers to do so themselves, wasting their strenght to kill each other to limit the spreading of corruption.\nStrategy.\nCare must be taken when engaging the Farron Followers, as while they are not very strong individually, they tend to swarm and overwhelm the player with their numbers. It is important to try to single out weak or vulnerable Followers and kill them quickly, in order to avoid being overpowered by the others. All Followers have very little &lt;a href=\"Poise%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Poise&lt;/a&gt; and little health, and as such they will typically fall in a few hits and can be stun-locked.\nThe Lancers can be defeated before aggro-ing the others with good ranged attacks, such as with a bow. Their projectiles are not hard to dodge, but their greatest danger lies in hitting the player with their spears in the midst of combat with other Followers, staggering them at inopportune times. They also pose very little threat at close range, and it can be relatively easy to roll through a projectile and then bear down on the Lancer before he can ready another one.\nKnights pose a danger more with their shields than with their attacks. Their shields can deflect a player's attacks if using smaller weapons like &lt;a href=\"Straight%20Swords%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Straight Swords&lt;/a&gt;, leaving them wide open for retaliation. This can prove problematic when embroiled in melee combat with different Follower types, as swinging wildly can cause the player's strikes to deflect at inconvenient moments. It is best to either avoid directly engaging them until other serious threats have been dealt with, or eliminate them immediately with a guard break followed by a riposte.\nTorchmen can deal a tremendous amount of damage if they can get within range to use their torches. They will generally breathe flames in streamed arcs, weaving back and forth in an attempt to hit the player multiple times in a single attack. If threatened at melee range, they will often breathe fire while backing away, in an attempt to avoid being caught by the player's attacks. The best way to deal with Torchmen is to roll through their initial fire stream and hit them with a rolling attack to stagger them and interrupt them, and then continue attacking until they are dead.\nSwordsmen will move aggressively on the player and chain together multiple slashes with their sabres. The best way to eliminate them is to block their attacks with a shield, and then strike when they are recovering."}
{"id": "150657", "revid": "5064773", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=150657", "title": "Farron Followers", "text": ""}
{"id": "131152", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=131152", "title": "Farron Greatsword", "text": "The Farron Greatsword is a &lt;a href=\"Boss%20Soul%20Items%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;soul-transposed&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Ultra%20Greatswords%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;ultra greatsword&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nAvailability.\nObtained by transposing the &lt;a href=\"Soul%20of%20the%20Blood%20of%20the%20Wolf\"&gt;Soul of the Blood of the Wolf&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href=\"Ludleth%20of%20Courland\"&gt;Ludleth of Courland&lt;/a&gt; at no soul cost.\nCharacteristics.\nThe Farron Greatsword is a unique two-piece weapon that caters towards quality builds leaning towards &lt;a href=\"Dexterity%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Dexterity&lt;/a&gt;. It is one of the lightest weapons in the ultra greatsword category, and its attacks consume very little stamina for its class. Its attacks can deal solid damage, making it a powerful weapon in the right hands.\nFunctioning similarly to &lt;a href=\"Paired%20Weapons\"&gt;Paired Weapons&lt;/a&gt;, two-handing will equip the dagger in the off-hand, yielding unique attack combos and allowing the wielder to &lt;a href=\"Parry%20and%20Riposte%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;parry&lt;/a&gt; with the dagger. The dagger combos can yield strong stun-locking potential, while also providing the wielder with strong offensive momentum and wide sweeping attacks. However, the inability to hold the weapon in both hands is also a crucial flaw, as all attacks performed by this weapon short of the jumping attack can be parried, a disadvantage that is not shared by any other ultra greatsword.\nAs with the &lt;a href=\"Wolf%20Knight%27s%20Greatsword\"&gt;Wolf Knight's Greatsword&lt;/a&gt;, the Farron Greatsword deals bonus damage to enemies rooted in the &lt;a href=\"Abyss\"&gt;Abyss&lt;/a&gt;. This makes it particularly strong against enemies such as &lt;a href=\"Darkwraith%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Darkwraiths&lt;/a&gt; and numerous foes in &lt;a href=\"The%20Ringed%20City\"&gt;The Ringed City&lt;/a&gt;, including the first phase of &lt;a href=\"Slave%20Knight%20Gael\"&gt;Slave Knight Gael&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "133924", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=133924", "title": "Farron Hail", "text": "Farron Hail is a &lt;a href=\"Sorcery%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;sorcery&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nAvailability.\nSold by &lt;a href=\"Orbeck%20of%20Vinheim\"&gt;Orbeck of Vinheim&lt;/a&gt; for 5,000 &lt;a href=\"Souls%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;souls&lt;/a&gt; once he has been given the &lt;a href=\"Sage%27s%20Scroll\"&gt;Sage's Scroll&lt;/a&gt;.\nEffect.\nThe caster charges the catalyst for a short period, and then unleashes a barrage of soul darts in a spread in front of the caster, in four waves of five darts each (for a maximum of 20 total darts). Each wave inflicts 0.58 times the catalyst's &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Buff\"&gt;Spell Buff&lt;/a&gt; as &lt;a href=\"Magic%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Magic&lt;/a&gt; damage to any targets hit. It does not matter how many darts hit a target in each wave, the damage from a wave that strikes a target is always the same.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Focus%20Points\"&gt;FP&lt;/a&gt; cost is expressed as a per-wave basis, with a potential cost of 16 FP for all four waves (12 FP with &lt;a href=\"Dusk%20Crown%20Ring%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Dusk Crown Ring&lt;/a&gt; equipped). Should the caster have enough FP for one wave but not all four, all waves will be cast regardless.\n&lt;br&gt;"}
{"id": "130749", "revid": "1188343", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=130749", "title": "Farron Keep", "text": "The Farron Keep is a in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\". It is a subsection of the &lt;a href=\"Road%20of%20Sacrifices\"&gt;Road of Sacrifices&lt;/a&gt;.\nDescription.\nThe Farron Keep is home to the &lt;a href=\"Abyss%20Watchers\"&gt;Abyss Watchers&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Watchdogs%20of%20Farron\"&gt;Watchdogs of Farron&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Covenant%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;covenant&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe entrance to the Farron Keep is at the bottom of a ladder coming from the &lt;a href=\"Road%20of%20Sacrifices%23Bonfires\"&gt;Crucifixion Woods&lt;/a&gt;. From here, you can see that much of the Farron Keep is in ruins and the few structures that remain are the three flaming towers, which need to be extinguished to open the way forward.\nThe surrounding area is covered in a sprawling &lt;a href=\"Poison%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;poisonous&lt;/a&gt; swamp, some parts of which are waist-deep and significantly hinder your movement. It is filled with &lt;a href=\"Rotten%20Slug\"&gt;Rotten Slug&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"Ghru\"&gt;Ghru&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"Elder%20Ghru\"&gt;Elder Ghru&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"Basilisk%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Basilisks&lt;/a&gt;, and somewhere lurks a lone &lt;a href=\"Darkwraith%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Darkwraith&lt;/a&gt;. Deep in this swamp stands a tower where the &lt;a href=\"Old%20Wolf%20of%20Farron\"&gt;Old Wolf of Farron&lt;/a&gt; lies, along with the &lt;a href=\"Dreamchaser%27s%20Ashes\"&gt;Dreamchaser's Ashes&lt;/a&gt;. An elevator leads up to the ruined bridge, where the &lt;a href=\"Stray%20Demon%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Stray Demon&lt;/a&gt; resides. Beyond the gate on the bridge are a small number of &lt;a href=\"Hollow%20Soldier%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Hollow Soldiers&lt;/a&gt;, three &lt;a href=\"Crystal%20Lizard%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Crystal Lizards&lt;/a&gt;, and some dragonslayer relics near a dead &lt;a href=\"Lothric%20Wyvern\"&gt;wyvern&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter the third flaming tower is extinguished, the door to the next area opens. Beyond it is a stretch of forest where a group of &lt;a href=\"Corvian\"&gt;Corvian&lt;/a&gt;s surrounds a &lt;a href=\"Corvian%20Storyteller\"&gt;Corvian Storyteller&lt;/a&gt; on a ledge, and further on are two &lt;a href=\"Darkwraith%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Darkwraiths&lt;/a&gt; on their way to clash with a group of &lt;a href=\"Ghru\"&gt;Ghru&lt;/a&gt;s in front of the mausoleum. To the right is the &lt;a href=\"Farron%20Keep%23Bonfires\"&gt;Farron Keep Perimeter&lt;/a&gt;, which leads back to the poisonous swamp and the &lt;a href=\"Road%20of%20Sacrifices%23Bonfires\"&gt;Crucifixion Woods&lt;/a&gt;, with a &lt;a href=\"Ravenous%20Crystal%20Lizard\"&gt;Ravenous Crystal Lizard&lt;/a&gt; along the way.\nDefeating the &lt;a href=\"Abyss%20Watchers\"&gt;Abyss Watchers&lt;/a&gt; can be done with the help of &lt;a href=\"Black%20Hand%20Gotthard\"&gt;Black Hand Gotthard&lt;/a&gt;. Once they are defeated, the way to the &lt;a href=\"Catacombs%20of%20Carthus\"&gt;Catacombs of Carthus&lt;/a&gt; opens.\nBonfires.\nThe Farron Keep is a subsection of the &lt;a href=\"Road%20of%20Sacrifices\"&gt;Road of Sacrifices&lt;/a&gt; and comprises the following &lt;a href=\"Bonfire%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;bonfires&lt;/a&gt;:"}
{"id": "138506", "revid": "5064773", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=138506", "title": "Farron Keep Perimeter", "text": ""}
{"id": "134129", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=134129", "title": "Farron Ring", "text": "The Farron Ring is a &lt;a href=\"Rings%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;ring&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nEffect.\nReduces &lt;a href=\"skill\"&gt;skill&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Focus%20Points\"&gt;FP&lt;/a&gt; consumption by 25%. Reduced FP cost is rounded up to the nearest point, so additional FP is only saved per 4 points of increased cost of a skill (e.g., a skill that would cost 16 FP is reduced by 4 points, and a skill that would cost 19 FP is also reduced by 4 points)."}
